SEC. 3. The Abaca Development Program envisioned in this Act shall be under the administrative supervision and control of the Secretary of Agriculture and Natural Resources, through a Board composed of the Director of the Bureau of Agricultural Extension, the Director of the Bureau of Plant Industry, the Manager of the Fiber Inspection Service, three representatives of the three abaca-producing regions and one representative of the Philippine Abaca Federation, Inc., and shall cover the following phases considered necessary to attain the primary objective to bring to at least the pre-war level the production of abaca fiber, popularly known as Manila hemp, and to reduce the cost of production in order to compete successfully with

sisal, henequene

and synthetic fibers; and finally, to achieve the desired level of Philippine export of abaca to the world market, as follows:

1.Abaca seed production and distribution to rehabilitate the present depleted abaca plantations;

2.Improvement of fiber extraction methods;

3.Development, and promotion of cottage industries using abaca as raw material;

4.Abaca research;

5.Abaca foreign trade promotion, and

6.General administration.
